# END OF LOG FILE
# 
# NOTES FOR STUDENTS:
# - Look for patterns of suspicious API calls:
#   * Multiple 403 (Forbidden) errors → Attempted unauthorized access
#   * Requests to /api/admin/* endpoints from external IPs
#   * DELETE methods on critical resources
#   * Attempts to access /api/backup, /api/database, /api/system
#   * Sequential access to multiple account IDs (enumeration attack)
#   * PUT/POST methods to modify passwords or balances
# 
# - Suspicious IPs show patterns of:
#   * Endpoint enumeration (trying many different endpoints)
#   * Privilege escalation attempts (admin, system, database endpoints)
#   * Data exfiltration attempts (export, backup, download)
#   * Destructive actions (DELETE methods, clear logs)
# 
# - The spike on 2025-12-08 22:00 (evening before the attack) is particularly suspicious
#   → This shows coordination between multiple attacker IPs
#   → This preceded the actual ransomware attack on 2025-12-15
# 
# - Use Python Pandas to analyze:
#   * Count of requests per IP
#   * Count of 403/401 errors per IP
#   * Most targeted endpoints
#   * HTTP methods distribution (GET vs POST/PUT/DELETE)
#   * Time-based patterns (unusual hours)
